translated: Ivarsson, Gustaf Wilhelm, county physician, Ljungskile, born on June 24, 1896, in Spjutstorp, Kristianstad. Married in 1932 to Helga Caroia Cecilia Carlsson. He graduated from Lund University with a high school diploma in 1916, a bachelor's degree in medicine in 1921, and a medical license in Stockholm in 1927. He served as acting assistant physician at Kronprinsessan Victorias kustsanatorium in 1922, as deputy physician at the Vadstena Hospital in 1924, as deputy physician at Strängnäs Hospital in 1925, as acting municipal physician in Spånga from 1927 to 1928, as acting county physician in Tingsryd district in 1928 and 1930, in Byske district in 1928, in Öckerö district in 1930, as a physician at the tuberculosis hospital in Boden from 1933 to 1934, as a deputy county physician in Kristdala district from 1934 to 1937, as a county physician in Mörsils district and health and railroad physician in 1937, and currently as a county physician in Ljungskile district. He had military medical training as a field medical officer in Fik in 1926 and as a battalion physician there in 1928. He was a battalion physician at the command in Boden and assistant physician at the Garnison hospital in Boden's medical and epidemic departments from 1930 to 1934, a battalion physician in Fik in 1934, and on reserve duty in 1937.
